This paper presents a new approach for computing posterior probabilities in Bayesian nets, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the problem of triangulation, which is related to graph theory and combinatorial optimization (cs.DM). The proposed approach involves decomposing the Bayesian net into smaller components, which can be seen as a form of graph partitioning (cs.SI). Finally, the paper involves passing messages between nodes in a tree structure, which is a common technique in information theory (cs.IT).
